To solve this, we first condense the absolute value inequality to remove the absolute.
\begin{align*} -16 & \le \lvert2x+7\rvert \le 16 \\ -16 & \le 2x+7 \le 16 \\ 12 & \le 2x \le 9  \\ 6 & \le x \le 4.5 \end{align*}
Since $x$ needs to be the least integer value, our answer is $\boxed{5}$.  <answer> $5$  </answer>

So let's first set up the ratio between white balls and red balls as a fraction. While the numerator represents white balls and the denominator represents red balls. Given that the ratio between white balls and red balls is $3:2$, then we can write: white balls / red balls =$3/2$Rewriting we get: red balls / white balls = $2/3$, so that: number of red balls / 9 = $2/3$$\begin{aligned}

&\phantom{\rule{2em}{0ex}}

&\phantom{\rule{2em}{0ex}}\frac{\text{number of red balls}}{9}

&=\frac{2}{3}\\

\\

\\\

&\phantom{\rule{2em}{0ex}}\text{number of red balls}

&=\frac{2}{3}{\color{#9A00aa}{9}}

&=\boxed{{\color{#377eb8}{6}}}

end{aligned}$
The answer is 6 red balls.

Denote $z = x + yi$, where $x$ and $y$ are real numbers. Then, we have</think>
\begin{align*}\left| \frac{z - 4}{z - 8} \right| &= 1 \Rightarrow \left| \frac{x + yi - 4}{x + yi - 8} \right| = 1,\text{ and using the definition of the absolute value to get}\end{align*}
\begin{align*}\frac{\sqrt{(x - 4)^2 + y^2}}{\sqrt{(x - 8)^2 + y^2}} &= 1 \Rightarrow \sqrt{(x - 4)^2 + y^2} = \sqrt{(x - 8)^2 + y^2},\\
\sqrt{x^2 - 8x + 16 + y^2} &= \sqrt{x^2 - 16x + 64 + y^2} \Rightarrow x^2 - 8x + 16 + y^2 = x^2 - 16x + 64 + y^2.\end{align*}
Thus, $8x = 48 \Rightarrow x = 6.$ This implies $z = 6 + yi.$</think>
\begin{align*}\left| \frac{z - 12}{z - 8i} \right| &= \frac{5}{3} \Rightarrow \left| \frac{6 + yi - 12}{6 + yi - 8i} \right| = \frac{5}{3},\text{ and we get}\end{align*}
\begin{align*}\frac{\sqrt{(-6 + yi)^2}}{\sqrt{(6 - 8i + yi)^2}} &= \frac{5}{3} \Rightarrow \frac{\sqrt{36 - 12yi - y^2}}{\sqrt{36 - 48i + 64 - 12yi - y^2}} = \frac{5}{3}.\end{align*}
Doing some algebra gives $36 - 12yi - y^2 = 25 - 20i - \frac{25}{9}y^2.$</think>
\[36 - y^2 = 25 - \frac{25}{9}y^2 \Rightarrow \frac{25}{9}y^2 + y^2 = 11 \Rightarrow y = \pm\sqrt{9} = \pm3.\]
Thus, the complex numbers $z$ are $\boxed{6 + 3i, 6 - 3i}.$</think>
</answer>

